article.headline: Suns win fourth straight game
article.linkText: Stoudemire (33 points), Suns shine bright in L.A.
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Phoenix Suns are loaded on offense. Just ask the Los Angeles Clippers. Amare Stoudemire overcame early foul trouble to score 33 points -- his fourth straight 30-point game -- and three other Suns players had at least 22 to help Phoenix defeat the Clippers 122-111 on Sunday for their fourth straight victory. Stoudemire scored nine of his points in the final 3:36 after the Clippers sliced a 20-point third-quarter deficit to six. "I came back with a vengeance in the second half," Stoudemire said. "The first half kind of got away from me because of a couple of early fouls. My teammates needed me, so I came back and played a lot smarter." Steve Nash had 22 points and 18 assists for the Suns, who improved to 8-2 and matched their best start since going 9-1 in 1980-81. Joe Johnson added 23 points and Shawn Marion 22. Quentin Richardson, playing his first regular-season game at Staples Center since leaving the Clippers for free agency, had 11 points in 30 minutes before fouling out. "They had four guys with 20 or more points -- and the only starter that didn't was Quentin Richardson, who we all know is a proven scorer," Clippers forward Elton Brand said. "So they had a lot of options and spread the floor." Nash's 18 assists boosted his league-leading average to 12.2 per game. "Steve makes it a lot easier because he's so creative," said Stoudemire, the beneficiary of five of Nash's assists. "He pretty much demands a double team because he shoots the ball so well and he has the screen-and-roll down to perfection." Marko Jaric scored 19 points for Los Angeles. Brand, playing on a sore left knee, had 17. The game marked Kerry Kittles's Clippers debut after recovery from knee surgery in June took longer than expected. He finished with two points in 24 minutes. "My knee and my legs weren't that much of an issue. But my timing was definitely off, which was expected because I hadn't played," said Kittles, who came over from New Jersey in the offseason. "The leg feels pretty good right now, and it's just a matter of getting my rhythm back on the court and learning to play with these guys." Phoenix extended a 13-point halftime lead to 76-56 on Stoudemire's layup with 8:17 left in the third quarter. The Clippers gradually chipped away and got as close as 105-99 on four consecutive free throws by Quinton Ross, capping an 11-2 run with 6:09 to play. The Suns, who entered averaging a league-leading 106.1 points, were 11-for-19 from 3-point range and shot 53.7 percent overall. Stoudemire picked up two fouls in the first 2:41 and was replaced by Steven Hunter for the rest of the opening quarter as Phoenix fell behind 29-24. But Stoudemire was back on the floor for the start of the second and scored six points during a 30-4 run that helped the Suns turn a nine-point deficit into a 54-37 lead with 3:32 left in the half.

Game notes
The last player with four straight 30-point games for the Suns was Charles Barkley in 1995-96. ... Los Angeles placed rookie G Lionel Chalmers on the injured list because of tendinitis in his left knee. ... Phoenix is 6-1 on the road. Last season, the Suns didn't win their sixth road game until Jan. 27, and finished 11-30 away from America West Arena. ... The Suns have outscored their opponent in the second quarter of all 10 games, including a 39-21 advantage against the Clippers.
